    <section>
      <title>An Introductory <m>\omega</m>-length Game</title>
      <slide>
        <title>The Cantor Game</title>
        <p>
Let <m>W\subseteq\mathbb R</m>.
Then <m>CG(W)</m> denotes the following game played by players <m>I</m>
and <m>II</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
During round <m>0</m>, <m>I</m> chooses some real number <m>a_0</m>,
followed by <m>II</m> choosing <m>b_0</m> such that <m>a_0\lt b_0</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
During round <m>n+1</m>, <m>I</m> chooses <m>a_{n+1}\in(a_n,b_n)</m>,
followed by <m>II</m> choosing <m>b_{n+1}\in(a_{n+1},b_n)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
After <m>\omega</m>-many rounds, <m>I</m> wins this game in the case
that <m>\lim_{n\to\infty}a_n\in W</m>.
        </p>
      </slide>
      <slide>
        <title>Strategies</title>
        <p>
I've yet to finish playing a single <m>\omega</m>-length game. :-(
        </p>
        <p>
However, both players in such a game can define <em>strategies</em>
that describe how they <em>would</em>...
        </p>
      </slide>
